CONCLUSION

This project investigated five different prompt engineering techniques and their impact on Large Language Model performance.

The study revealed that prompt design significantly influences response quality. Zero-shot prompting is efficient for simple tasks but offers limited control. Few-shot prompting improves consistency through examples. Role prompting successfully alters communication style and audience targeting. Chain-of-Thought prompting enhances logical reasoning and problem-solving. Tree-of-Thought prompting provides the most comprehensive analysis by evaluating multiple solution paths.

Among all techniques, Tree-of-Thought produced the highest-quality responses for complex decision-making tasks, while Chain-of-Thought excelled in mathematical and logical reasoning. The findings demonstrate the importance of selecting an appropriate prompting strategy based on task requirements.

Future work may include testing additional techniques such as Self-Consistency Prompting, ReAct Prompting, and Retrieval-Augmented Prompting to further improve LLM performance.
